NoSQL

   NoSQL databases.
     * Column-Family
          + [http://hbase.apache.org/]Apache HBase - Hadoop database, a
            distributed, big data store.
          + [http://cassandra.apache.org/]Cassandra - Distributed DBMS
            designed to handle large amounts of data across many servers.
          + [http://hypertable.org/]Hypertable - C++ based BigTable-like
            DBMS, communicates through Thrift and runs either as
            stand-alone or on distributed FS such as Hadoop.
     * Document Store
          + [http://couchdb.apache.org/]CouchDB - Ease of use, with
            multi-master replication document-oriented database system.
          + [https://www.elastic.co/]ElasticSearch - Java based database,
            popular with log aggregation, and email archiving projects.
          + [https://www.mongodb.org/]MongoDB - Another document-oriented
            database system.
          + [http://ravendb.net/]RavenDB - Document based database with
            ACID/Transactional features.
          + [http://www.rethinkdb.com/]RethinkDB - Distributed document
            store database, focuses on JSON.
     * Graph
          + [https://github.com/twitter/flockdb]FlockDB - Twitter's
            distributed, fault-tolerant graph database.
          + [http://neo4j.com/]Neo4j - Graph database.
     * Key-Value
          + [https://github.com/google/leveldb]LevelDB - Google's high
            performance key/value database.
          + [http://redis.io/]Redis - Networked, in-memory, key-value data
            store with optional durability.
          + [http://basho.com/riak/]Riak - Another fault-tolerant
            key-value NoSQL database.

   Comparison of NoSQL servers:
   [http://kkovacs.eu/cassandra-vs-mongodb-vs-couchdb-vs-redis]http://kkov
   acs.eu/cassandra-vs-mongodb-vs-couchdb-vs-redis

